text: SPOILER ALERT TO ANYONE WHO HASN'T FINISHED ALLEGIANT. DON'T READ THIS IF YOU DONT WANT TO KNOW THE ENDING. To everyone complaining about how Tris ends up dying, was it really a surprise? Tris has shown throughout the whole trilogy how she would be willing to give her life to save another's, did we really think that she would let her own brother die while she stood by? And she was right about being able to resist the death serum, she just wasn't expecting someone to be armed in the weapons lab. Don't get me wrong, I found it just as heartbreaking as everyone else. But I do think that is was an appropriate ending to a wonderful series. It showed that sometimes you have to give up everything for what is right.  I'm such a huge fan of this trilogy and I'm so excited to see this movie!

text: You all should stop calling it a Hunger games rip off, hunger games is about kids fighting each other to death for national TV, Divergent is a about a society that is divided into 5 factions and at first seems okay but later it crumbles. Is about this girl who chooses to leave her family and her original faction because she didn't feel like she fitted in. Most of the book is about her going through the initiation of her new faction and her finding out what Divergent is and why it is so dangerous. So I now dare you to tell me how is this a rip off the hunger games because the only similar thing they have is that the main character is a female and that's it. It doesn't even have a love triangle and the love story isn't rushed or even the focus of the story, is about the characters as individuals. SO NOW SHUT UP.

text: For everyone who is comparing Divergent to The Hunger Games, they're totally different stories with totally different meanings and you obviously didn't read the books. The Hunger Games is about standing up for what you believe in, even if you don't want to. But none the less, they're both amazing stories.

text: the dock, as lines of convicts labour beneath him on the steep steps of the dock wall. Behind Javert, through the storm rain we glimpse a forest of half-built ships, their ribbed frames like great skeletons in the mist. FOREGROUND convicts are at work on another ship that is almost completed, labouring in the crashing spray. CONVICT 2 I've done no wrong Sweet Jesus, hear my prayer! CONVICTS Look down, look down Sweet Jesus doesn't care. CONVICT 5 I know she'll wait I know that she'll be true - CONVICTS Look down, look down They've all forgotten you. CONVICT 1 When I get free You won't see me Here for dust! 3. CONVICTS Look down, look down Don't look'em in the eye. CONVICT 3 How long, O Lord Before you let me die? CONVICTS Look down, look down You'll always be a slave. Look down, look down You're standing in your grave. With a last great heave the lines of convicts haul the damaged ship onto the slipway. CRACK! The stern flagpole of the ship snaps in a vicious gust of wind and crashes down into the shallow water near Valjean. Javert sees and points his stick at Valjean in silent command. Valjean stares back for a beat, defying him. Then he drops down into the seething water and re-emerges with the great mast in his hands, held over his head. His head breaks water with his bitter gaze still on Javert, as he throws the mast ashore in a deliberate display of strength. Javert nods to the guards, and they begin to form the chained men into lines to return to their prison. The storm is passing now, blown by the driving wind. Javert approaches Jean Valjean. JAVERT Now Prisoner 24601. Your time is up And your parole's begun. You know what that means? VALJEAN Yes. It means I'm free. JAVERT No! It means you get Your yellow ticket-of-leave. He hands Valjean a folded yellow paper. JAVERT This badge of shame You'll show it everywhere. It warns you're a dangerous man. VALJEAN I stole a loaf of bread My sister's child was close to death And we were starving. 4. JAVERT You will starve again Unless you learn the meaning of the law. VALJEAN I know the meaning of those nineteen years A slave of the law! JAVERT Five years for what you did, The rest because you tried to run. Yes, 24601! VALJEAN My name is Jean Valjean! JAVERT And I'm Javert! Do not forget my name. Do not forget me - 24601! He strides away to command the lines of convicts as they're marched away. Valjean walks away, hardly able to take in that he is free at last. The convicts sing as he goes. CONVICTS Look down, look down You'll always be a slave. Look down, look down You're standing in your grave. 2 EXT. ROAD OUT OF TOULON - DAWN 2 Valjean makes his way up a rising track, a worn knapsack on his back. He comes to a stop at the top of the hill, and there before him, lit by the rising sun, spreads a wide vista of fields and towns and villages, stretching into the distance, with the snow capped Alps beyond. Behind and below him lies Toulon at the sea's edge. As we hear the musical theme ('Freedom is Mine'), we see for the first time the darkness in his face give way to a new hope. VALJEAN Freedom at last - How strange the taste! Never forget the years - the waste, Nor forgive them for what they've done. They are the guilty - Everyone! The day begins (more) 5. VALJEAN (cont'd) And now lets see What this new world Will do for me! 3 SCENE OMITTED 3 4 EXT. COUNTRY ROAD - DAY 4 Valjean strides down the long rising road, pulling his thin coat close round him against the cold winter wind. He passes a long line of labourers working. He approaches the OVERSEER. VALJEAN Monsieur can I help? A day's work? The overseer notices shaved hair showing under his cap. OVERSEER Take your hat off. Valjean takes his hat off, revealing his shaved and scarred head. OVERSEER Passport. The overseer scans the yellow paper, and hands it back. OVERSEER No work here. 5 SCENE OMITTED 5 6 EXT. MOUNTAIN ROAD - END OF DAY 6 Valjean slogs on up the rising track into the mountains. Snow on the ground here, and darkness falling. He looks up and sees ahead a village built on a rock cliff, its lights twinkling, the snowy mountains rising behind. The tower of its handsome church rises up like a promise of refuge. This is Digne. 6A EXT. DIGNE - DUSK 6A Valjean enters Digne. As he drinks from the fountain, he sees a guard standing outside the Mairie. 6. 6B INT. MAIRIE, DIGNE - DUSK 6B Valjean stands waiting. The officer fastidiously writes down the name of Valjean in his huge ledger and the name of the town in his passport. The officer signs and stamps the passport. OFFICER Valjean. The officer hands back the passport. Valjean leaves. 6C EXT. DIGNE - DUSK 6C Valjean walks down the high street, spies the warm glow of an inn and enters. 7 INT. COUNTRY INN, DIGNE - DUSK 7 Valjean sits in the corner, his hat low over his head. He eyes hungrily a group of cart drivers tucking into a roast meal by a roaring fire place. The innkeeper serves him a beer. As he reaches for it his coat sleeve rides up to reveal his wrist, calloused and scarred by manacles. The innkeeper eyes him warily. He discusses Valjean with two other men, then asks for his paper. Sees the phrase "Extremely Dangerous". VALJEAN'S POV - From the yellow paper in the innkeeper's hands up to the innkeeper's face. A blank stare, a shrug of refusal. INNKEEPER My inn is full. 7A EXT. DIGNE - NIGHT 7A Valjean moves off wearily through the village. As he passes down the narrow street, faces peer at him from doorways, but the doors close when he goes by. A shadowy figure follows him. Word has spread that he's a `dangerous man'. Passing the uncurtained window of a cottage, he comes to a stop. Through the window he sees a scene that breaks his heart: a father at a table by lamplight, his young wife before him, his children on either side. Nothing special, and yet everything he's never had. 8 EXT. PRISON, DIGNE - NIGHT 8 He stops at the local jail. An iron chain attached to a bell hangs from the prison door. He rings. A grate slides open. 7. VALJEAN Jailer. Would you let me stay here for tonight? JAILER This is a prison, not an inn. Get yourself arrested. Then we will open up for you. The grate slides shut. As Jean Valjean walks away, some children who have been following begin throwing stones at him. He threatens them with his stick and they scatter. 8A EXT. DIGNE - NIGHT 8A He sees over a garden wall a low doorway in a stone turret. Valjean stoops through the doorway and lies down on some straw. He hears a ferocious growl and sees the head of an enormous mastiff. It is a dog kennel. 8B EXT. DIGNE - NIGHT 8B Snow falling as Valjean makes his way down the road, hungry, weary, moving slowly, his trousers ripped and bloody from where the dog has bitten him. At the end of a road, the snow-covered church; beside it, a dark churchyard. 9 EXT. CHURCH YARD, DIGNE - NIGHT 9 Snow-covered gravestones in moonlight. Exhausted, Valjean collapses to the ground and huddles himself into the shelter of a doorway. A lantern glows in the dark. The lantern approaches, throwing shadows. Its little circle of light comes to rest on the crumpled figure of Valjean. He stirs and opens his eyes. VALJEAN'S POV - The glow of the lantern in the darkness. Beyond it, the half-seen features of a kind old man. The BISHOP. BISHOP Come in, sir, for you are weary And the night is cold out here. Though our lives are very humble What we have we have to share. Bewildered, fearful, suspicious, Valjean gets up and goes with the Bishop into the house by the church. 8. 10 INT. BISHOP'S HOUSE - NIGHT 10 A simple table on which is laid out bread and wine, with silver cutlery. Two silver candlesticks light the room, illuminating walls painted with religious scenes. The Bishop ushers the bewildered Valjean into the room. The bishop's sister Madame Baptistine stands. Valjean hesitates. BISHOP There is wine here to revive you. There is bread to make you strong. There's a bed to rest till morning - Rest from pain, and rest from wrong. BISHOP Sit, my brother. The Bishop gestures to the housekeeper Madame Magloire. BISHOP Madame, set one more place. (to Valjean) Please sit. The Bishop gently takes his arm and draws him into a chair. Valjean sits, and the Housekeeper lays food before him. Famished, Valjean eats like an animal. Divergent is a complete different story from these two series, yes there is a love story and yes there is a rebellion again the government. Tris is faced with these decisions and to make things even more difficult is the fact that she doesn't fit into a particular faction because she is Divergent. Divergents basically have multiple traits from each factions which makes them extremely dangerous because they DONT CONFORM into a faction or into society for that matter which is why, "they need to be eliminated" according to Jeanine Matthews.

text: People who are comparing it to THG. STOP!!!! This story is about a girl trying discover who she truly is ,and the difficulties of going in a direction foreign to your parents , in a society where she must conform. the THG series is a fight where all  districts unite, against the government because of how they are treating them carelessly and having them kill each other off, for the Capitol's entertainment. Yes in Divergent there is a fight towards the government but that's not even the main plot and not everyone is against it (the government) and how different the fight is from THG will shock you, but I'm not going to spoil that. Please stop comparing, these two stories that have nothing in common except the female protagonist and the dystopian worlds. They are both great books. If you haven't read Divergent, I would advise you to read it, before the movie comes out in March 21st. Thank you.

text: Dystopian is a genre, just because something is in the same genre doesn't mean that everythong about them is the same! The Hunger Games and Divergent have different plots and ate different dystopian worlds.  In the Hunger Games kid are "reaped" or chosen to participate in a "game" where they must fight to the death for national tv. The only people who find it entertaining are the rich people though.  In Divergent there are 5 different factions that stand for different values. There is a test to see witch faction you fit into. You are "divergent" if you qualify for more than one faction.  See they are NOT the same!  Just because the main story line is about a world run by the government and people start a rebellion for the two stories does not mean they are the same!  Divergent is not stealing the fans of the Hunger Games- they share fans!  I hope that cleared up a bit of the debate going on!

text: Okay, what I'm going to say may contain some SPOILERS, so if you wanted to read Hunger Games or Divergent, you don't have to read this. Similarities: Dystopian Genre, people are placed into groups, takes place in the future, female protagonist, violence, competition, and etc. Differences: In Divergent, the factions are based on traits, in Hunger Games, the districts are based on productions(fishing, mining, etc.)  that are given to the Capitol. In the Hunger Games, children aged 12-18 years old are FORCED to fight in the games because of District 13's rebellion. In Divergent, sixteen year olds take an aptitude test to see what faction do they belong in and they can CHOOSE to stay in the faction they are in or leave to go in a different faction, but as a consequence, they must leave their old ways and follow that faction's rules. In the Hunger Games, Katniss's sister, twelve year old sister, Prim is reaped to fight, but Katniss volunteers in her place to protect her. In Divergent, Beatrice doesn't feel like she belongs in her selfless faction. When she takes the aptitude test, she's told that her results were inconclusion, which means she's divergent. I'm not going to say what makes her Divergent, but being Divergent isn't like the chosen one because other people are divergent as well. So, Beatrice chooses Dauntless, a bravery faction, but there are these things that are like exams to us. In order to be admitted to that faction, you need to take those exams which you must be ranked in the top ten or you'll be dismissed and become factionless. So, basically,  in Divergent, it's all about belonging somewhere and the protagonist finds out that her society isn't perfect and that the people are corrupt. In the Hunger games, the government is corrupt, a lot of survival and a rebellion is formed. I hope that clears things up. So, as a fan of both the books, please read both the books and watch both the movies before judging.

text: Dear all young adult readers or movie watchers complaining about how Divergent is copying The Hunger Games,  One, you probably never heard of Divergent until the trailer was released. Just like you never read The Hunger Games until the movie was released, either. Seeing as I'm someone who read both way, way before the movies were released, I think I qualify as someone who can tell you YOU ARE WRONG.  Two, Just because both novels are dystopians, which is a GENRE, a subcategory of Fiction->Fantasy, does not mean they are the same. They have two completely different plots, which, not meaning to spoil anything because everything I'm about to say is on the book jackets and in the trailers, makes the two SEPARATE books. The Hunger Games is about a group of 12-17 year olds competing for their lives in a sanctioned government tournament. Divergent allows a sixteen year old to pick what faction he or she wants to belong to, while only following the rules and guidelines of that faction. Do these plots sounds similar to you?  Last, if you want proof that Dystopian novels existed L-O-N-G before The Hunger Games, I can name a few books for you. 1984, Farenheit 451 (well, anything by Ray Bradbury honestly), Brave New World, I Am Legend, and even a more recent one (released in 2005, three years prior to THG), Uglies by Scott Westerfeld.  I think your argument is clearly invalid, and that if you claim to be such an avid fan of dystopians, you clearly need to branch out more when it comes to literary works.  Sincerely, A Very Annoyed Dystopian Reader

text: To those asking about the premise of Divergent, it's a really hard story to explain. It is set in a dystopian Chicago where 5 factions based on personality exist. The problem is that society has fallen to this mindset, and some of the factions are actually superior to the others (i.e. the Erudite take advantage of the Dauntless).  As the story unfolds you see how society begins to suffer without realizing it but those that do see the corruption (mostly the Divergent and factionless) realize that they need to stop it, and must rid society of the faction system constraining them and making them vulnerable to each other.  This paints them as targets to those in power.  It comes full circle throughout the trilogy, but that's the basic taste :)

text: This trailer makes the movie look like it carries every square inch of the book, which I loved and read in a day, prompting me to buy the next two before reading a word of the second. Very interesting, although I hope they don't pull a Hunger Games and cut out all of the violence.  Not to spoil: The book is very calm and lays violence in very particular and ultra-focused turning point scenes, then goes fast paced forcing morally-ambiguous decisions in the climax. Without the threat of reality, it wouldn't be believable, and the message wouldn't come across.  With gruesome imagery, this movie could spark conversation and break though from novelty entertainment to mainstream consciousness, developing itself into a modern cornerstone of an inquisitive society. With close cutaways and bloodless corpses, it becomes laughable to the point of shame on an entire genre. Fingers crossed.

text: I am very excited and interested to see Shailene Woodley portray as Tris Prior. I kind of watched The Secret Life of an American Teenager but  it wasn't something I wanted to watch, but I've seen both her movies: The Descendants and The Spectacular Now, which were fantastic. Before judging her, please at least watch both those movies; she's a great actor. I've seen the B-roll of the movie and the acting seemed real. When it comes to acting, I don't like it when the actors 'act', I like to see if they are able to be the character and make the character real. Shailene is definitely listening and reacting to what the other characters is saying to her while performing the scenes, particularly the ferris wheel scene. In my opinion, I don't think the Secret Life did any justice, probably because of the story and script or because her acting was still developing that time. In addition to her acting, I am excited to see her portray as Hazel Grace in one of my favorite books: The Fault in Our Stars. On the other hand, I am disappointed that in The Amazing Spiderman 2, they had to cut her scenes out because I really wanted to see how differently she could portray Mary Jane, but it's completely understandable.   Therefore, even though she doesn't physically look like Tris, Shailene, an Independent Spirit award winner for best supporting actress and a Golden Globe nominee for best supporting actress is definitely the right choice to be Tris. Based on the trailer, with the background music and the surroundings, she's got this.

text: I can't see this being the next Hunger Games or anything even remotely close to that. And honestly, the Divergent book sucks. I'm reading it at the moment and there's absolutely nothing special in it. I'm halfway through it and I'm still force-reading into it and trying to like it but I can't. It's like there's no real goal or purpose to the story. With The Hunger Games, I just had to force myself to read the first sentence and then I found myself instantly pulled into the story. I couldn't stop. That's why it took me only a little over a week to finish reading the entire series. But Divergent is simply terrible. And even if you disagree with my opinion, which some people obviously will, I respect your views and opinion. But I simply cannot see this being the next Hunger Games, LOTR, or Harry Potter or anything close to them. At most, this is gonna be the next Twilight. And that's best case scenario as well. It'll get famous for the movies and die out once the movies are done, just like Twilight.

text: I cannot wait until 3/21/2014.However, I can tell from this trailer that the movie will deviate from the book but I hope not too much. The books were written beautifully with so much detail. I honestly see no reason to deviate.  Anyway, I am pleased that they cast Theo James as "Four". He is exactly what I envisioned he'd look like. As for Shaleene Woodley (I think that's her name), as Tris Prior, I was not sure about her until I read the 2nd and 3rd books of the series. I am now convinced they picked a great cast and I am glad we will see some relatively fresh faces on the screen come Spring. I do, however, wish casting directors would do a better job at choosing a diverse cast. I mean I get per the book it is fair to say the characters are possibly all white but it would have been nice to see them deviate from that aspect of the book and cast main not just supporting characters of all races, White, Black, Hispanic, Asian, etc. I guess even in a dystopian world not much has change in terms of hollywood. text: I think the trailer is throwing everyone off. As we go further into new clips and exclusives, it's easier to tell that it should be a pretty well done book adaptation. The public mostly assumes it's a rip off of The Hunger Games Trilogy, but really it's because the early advertisements that were put out in public that would put Divergent under that name of being the "New Hunger Games", but they didn't mean that in a literal way, so to speak. So that is why the public is reacting in this way, and people like myself who have read and enjoyed the book series tell and tell again that it's not a rip off of it, but it is only the dystopian world in YA books that makes these series so similar. I think it's fascinating to see different interpretations of our society's future, and we shouldn't be criticizing absurd similarities that the ones who are not familiar with the series are assuming by this one, confusing trailer, which in my opinion is very good but tells the plot and the definition of the film in an awkward and unstructured way. The trailers of a movie don't really demonstrate the movie's quality too much (but it's only to explain the simple plot) which is why people should not be so dramatic about it. Overall, the trailer tells the plot fairly well, and because I love the books so much and the story really interests me, my ticket is already sold.

text: I like the concept but it _seems_ like another cliche chick flick. So this is what I got out of this trailer: So it's about a girl in a utopian society, she is different from everybody. She's like a secret; or they will kill her if she's exposed. The gov't or anybody cant find out so the lady/conselor/whatever sends her to a underground training facility with people like her. She doesn't want to be in there anymore because it's dangerous so she *tries* to run away with a dude that's just like her that she met while in the facility (maybe a training partner). _Not shockingly_, they fall in love while being together in the mist of everybody turning on her.  _Okay_, we'll put in into layman's terms, or a tl;dr friendly.  A girl at risk runs away with a boy she falls in love with. It achingly lasts for three books. Adding gore into a romance doesn't make it 'badass'. Hell, I can just read Romeo and Juliet!  It's like sprinkling sugar on a pile of shit. I think people who _read the book_ is naturally grown to love this indirect romance movie. Other than that, people who didn't read the book is going to ask 'what the actual fuck did I just watch' after the trailer and/or movie. She's like the modern Illuminati of Divergent.  _Now if you want a legit pile of shit (aka chick flicks/romance) that actually looks and tastes good with sugar_, I suggest you read Drink, Slay, Love by Sarah Beth Durst. Plus, it has unicorns with genuine Dracula-like vampires in it.

text: After reading the long list of comments, I have become incredibly irritated by the extreme levels of ignorance portrayed by a lot of people. 1) The 'Divergent' book series is completely different from 'The Hunger Games' trilogy. I have read all of the books in both series' (except for 'Allegiant', which I plan to begin reading soon) and I can confidently say that they have completely different plot lines. Yes, they are both set in the future, but this is pretty much the only similarity. 2) To those of you who are judging the entire series based off of a two minute trailer, please get your facts straight. Haven't you ever heard of the saying "Never judge a book by its cover"? Divergent is most likely nothing you think it is. 3) Yes, there is romance in the story - but so what? Unlike most 'cliche' films/books, there is one love interest in the story, instead of a pathetically long drawn-out love triangle. Thank you for your time. I hope some of you have actually taken this information in.

text: Can someone who's read the books help me please ..  Ok- I'm about halfway through the first book and the only thing that's confused me so far is this: OK so the test tells you where you belong.. But you're allowed to either pick where you grew up, or, if its different from where you grew up, you can pick whatever you're test told you. BUT you're not allowed to discuss your results, so doesn't that make the test pointless? Like couldn't you just pick any faction even if you didn't grow up there OR get it as a result? Since no one knows I mean... Granted, this would be pretty dumb BC if you didn't belong there , you probably wouldn't pass their tests and end up factionless... But still... They didn't really explain it much so I'm having trouble understanding the point of the test. And its obviously a HUGE plot point lol so i want to understand! Is it just to show you where you're most likely to have the most success? So you have less chance of ending up factionless? And then if youd prefer to stay home you can? But if that's the case, why is it such a disgrace to leave your faction? I get its bad to leave your family but isn't the whole point that factions area the entire point of life lol so why would your family want you to risk picking where you don't most belong (and possibly fail initiation) just BC you grew up there. Also, if you dont have to stick w ur result .. Doesnt that make anyone who doesnt go w their test slightly divergent too (since they have traits of two factions?) Or does the test mean that's really what you are SOLELY (but then how do they pass initiation of their home faction if they truly don't belong there)? Hope this makes sense and isn't too all over the place... I'd appreciate anyone's ideas! Thanks and happy new year to everyone!   Really just wanna see if I missed something or am not understanding.. It could just be a minor plot hole, and if so then whatever bc the book is still great!  Thanks again (and sorry so long, clearly am confused lol)

text: Here's what I think about the casting of four/tobias. Everyone is complaining because theo is too buff and big. But I feel like when u read it from tris's point of view, only she could notice the small details of his long slender fingers and such. To everyone else, it felt like they saw four as this guy who just seemed like he belonged in dauntless. This guy with muscles and hard eyes. In insurgent, tris starts to notice his dark hair is actually brown and that he has freckles. Tris doesn't notice these things until insurgent, which proves how well he blended into the dauntless, like he always had belonged there. Also, keep in mind, it's not about how the actor looks. Katniss was described as small so when Jen was cast, I had my doubts, but obviously I was proven wrong. Just keep an open mind. You might be shocked to find theo might be the perfect four/Tobias.

text: I don't think people understand. THIS IS A MOVIE ADAPTATION. Theo and Shailene are not going to look exactly like Tobias and Tris, simply because, they are fictional. Both Veronica and Neil have said that they were perfect for the role and I'm not going to argue. This is not THE HUNGER GAMES, This book/film is finding out about who they truly are, and whether they can survive in the Faction, THE HUNGER GAMES is about killing people in an arena from different districts. I have read both trilogies and love them both. Again, they are going to add lines in because mainly the book is Tris' thoughts. And, if you're put off by the trailer because its not the book, don't watch the film then, simple as. It's going to be a great film. Also, people saying the test isn't the same as in the book, look what Tris is wearing, black, not grey, which makes me think this is the simulation test and they haven't showed the aptitude test, so, it is only a trailer. And people saying that Marcus was meant to make the speech that Jeanine took, is because they have a HUGE star Kate Winslet, it'd be idiotic not to give her a large role in the first film. Nuff said.

text: Okay ya know what I'm gettng pissed off! The hunger games is completely different than the divergent series and those of you saying "it's basically the same thing with a different title" yeah shame on you. You obviously haven't taken the time to read both book series and notice the large AND small differences. The Hunger Games series is about a male and female from each section to participate in a fight between other section members to win food for a year to their starving families making them the year's victors. In divergent it is about 5 different factions that all take part in the society they built for themselves protecting them from the outside world. And each 16 each year takes a simulation test telling them which faction they belong to based of personality traits. Two COMPLETELY different book series!

text: Since everyone thinks that people should read the books, I guess this is no problem;  Kids take a test at 16 to sort into brave, dumb, smart, and peaceful. The dumb rule, the peaceful is just like the dumb, but whatever. Some people are more then one of those things, and the smart don't like that. Our hero Tris is more then one thing. She is three things. So her mom, who is two things tells her to shut up and pretend. So Tris chooses brave. Her dad is dumb, but her brother wants to leave home to be smart. The smart are bad guys. they want to rule, because the dumb gave away all the food to the factionless. So the smart dope up the brave and send them off to kill the dumb. But the drug doesn't work on Tris and her hunky brave boyfriend, because both are divergent.They run to save the dumb. They scuffle around, and Tris' brave divergent mom is killed, as is her dumb dad. They save a few dumb, and all run off to hide at the second piggies house....I mean at the peaceful compound. THE END. I just hope to save people a few bucks. There are so many better books out there.i

text: When I watched this, I never imagined nor thought of The Hunger Games. I have read both trilogies, and though it sometimes resembles a little (the factions = districts) it doesn't fully say THE HUNGER GAMES. Tris and Katniss are two different people. Katniss already knows what the corrupt system is and is fighting against is as Tris slowly learns how the system works and tries to stop it because of the unfairness of it all. Both girls have the same goals, but the journey to get to those goals are ENTIRELY different and the events that happen in the book, same with the plot, are really different, and I hope people will give Divergent a chance because it's a really good book.

text: For all of you typical, namby-pamby cynics who are just going "lol, hunger games was better", please stop yourself. Because I could easily say that *1984* puts a series like the Hunger Games to shame and then make you feel like a trendy idiot, but then again, that wouldn't be fair because it puts just about every new dystopian fiction based book to shame because there is not a single dystopian book on the face of this planet better than *1984*, arguably one of the all-time greatest fiction books ever written. Why? Because unlike the Hunger Games or Divergent, the message of *1984* somehow predicted exactly how the world would be in the future from the time it was written. The Hunger Games or Divergent has yet to do the same.

ABC family's crappy scripts and crappy cinematography can make anyone seem like a crappy actor/actress)         Despite the thoroughly mediocre trailer, I still have high hopes for this movie. Because if you think about it, the book contains a lot of "reveals" and "plot twists" that you can't rightly put in the trailer. And outside of those twists, what can you put in the trailer? Fighting, jumping, and train hopping. Which makes for a movie trailer that looks like the life of a parkour gang. All in all, let's hope this is seen as " holy crap ANOTHER good movie franchise!" And not " uggghh god ANOTHER hunger games?".

text: I'm honestly getting tired of Hollywood selling out and making these generic teenage novel based movies. I mean,  they're all the exact same thing consisting of the exact same structure as the last teenage novel movie.   Think about it. You have your generic "most important" female main character who is suddenly the "chosen one" who is the only relevant character in the entire movie. You have your generic strong male supporting character who eventually has a love interest in the main female character after acting tough and "hard" throughout the story, and eventually a love triangle will ensue after another strong male character is introduced.  Don't forget the ending. We all know that Hollywood (and since this was produced by Summit) will drag out the story into either a saga or a trilogy, and anyone with a brain will know the ending even if they didn't read the book. I honestly don't even have to say the ending, but for those who don't have any common sense: the girl falls in love with a dude, and saves the dystopian world through her special abilities acquired just by being a main character. The End.  Seriously. Why do people insist on supporting Hollywood and letting them make all of these book based movies? Why support them and let them think that unoriginality makes the best movies? There are some books that NEED a movie adaptation, but please let me emphasis SOME. Not every book published by a youthful author needs to be made into a movie.

text: The movie was awesome but the biggest fault (in my opinion) was the severe lack of extras. There are almost 3 million people living in Chicago at the moment. In the future, that will be even more. And we're supposed to believe that there are only 40 sophomores/year 10 students in Dauntless, trying to qualify for 22 positions to make it in to that faction that year. So, if the other five factions took 40 initiates (of the same age) then that means there are only (roughly) 200 students in each grade (across all 5 factions). If that's the case, society would only be like 10,000 people, max. That doesn't seem like a very populous city. That seems like a really small town living in a massive city (Chicago) I come from a city of 5 million, and there were more than 200 people in my grade at school alone. The amount of people in my grade in the whole city would have been tens of thousands. There were only two scenes where it looked like there was a decent amount of extras and that was the choosing ceremony and when they did a bird's eye view of dauntless entering Abnegation. And even that was only a few hundred. You couldn't see their faces though, and most of the extras were CGI'd in more. I wish they had done this more, and made futuristic-Chicago looked like it has a more decent population. It really could have enhanced the world they were creating, and the future they were creating. Instead, it looked like the population of a high school, not an entire city like Chicago. This is something they took on board for Catching Fire though. The reaping ceremony looked really small and intimate. Then, in Catching Fire, all of a sudden Panem was ENORMOUS. You got to see the other districts and see thousands upon thousands of people in each district. I wish this were the case for Divergent, but hopefully they improve it in Insurgent and Allegiant. I doubt the extras would even need to be paid. So many people would do it for free, and then others would be pretty cheap, and you could CGI the same people into the background thousands of times. It just really took away from the "world building" because we're meant to believe this is an entire city, and all that we know that remains of the future, and it's just like 5 small grades in a small high school.

text: No Fear is what makes you dangerous. Euhm? No.. ever met a small dog? Lets fight a scared Spermwhale or elephant... ?  Its what you can do that's dangerous, ability to judge risks and feel fear isn't all that bad. Smart Systematical beings are just as dangerous as athletic fearless ones. Fear can even motivate.  Fear mostly change your stress level, and how the brain prioritise its signals and by that way its body functions. When you have a high stress you usually react with you primal brain that's closer to the spine,  Like fight or flee. You will not think things over and the cognitive process is mor basted on active perception. Witch prioritise the abilities you need for fight or flee most.  Anyhow, I get a bit annoyed by the scientific part in fiction movies. Don't explain it all, or don't try to make it make sense, you make it worse.

text: SO MUCH BETTER THAN HUNGER GAMES. i have read books for both and seen films for both and diveregent is by far more fast paced, more emotional, more creative etc. for hunger games it takes a whole fucking hour before they are even starting the games. i nearly fall asleep. divergents concept is so interesting, it tackles identity, courage etc. for people who haven't read the books there are different factions, each faction has a set of rules on how to live. when you are 16 you get to chose to stay in your faction or go to another one. BUT if you go to another faction, you can never return to yours. never live with your family etc and if you can't cope with the new society you chose, you become factionless aka homeless. i think the acting was great, i am glad they brought some new faces into the mix. the music was spot on and matched the scenes. the pacing was quick and they cut some of the emotional scenes from the book. so if you think this movie is going to be a hunger games rip off, or a slow, love story etc. you are wrong and i feel deeply sorry for you that you won't watch this greatness, due to the narrow minded people below.

text: I am seriously pissed off on the people who call this a THG or like Twilight rip off, because it's really not. **Might contain small spoilers** I cannot deny that THG and Divergent have their similarities, but they are far from being the same. Divergent is about five factions (that was created to keep peace) that all see equality (kind of at least) in eachother, but that there is people who have a mind that cannot be put in just one faction, and therefore is a "threat". The Hunger Games is about twelve districts being fully controlled and used by the capital for entertainment for example, but it's mostly focused on the "hunger games" where they force children to force eachother. I guess the biggest similarity is in Tris and Katniss. Two very brave and strong female caracthers who is not afraid to stand up for their self and others. And well, they also seem to insult people pretty often. I have read all the books in both series and I can assure you, there is a hell of a big difference if you think about it.

text: "With an adherence to YA formula that undercuts its individualistic message, Divergent opens its planned trilogy in disappointingly predictable fashion." - Divergent currently has a 41% negative rating on Rotten Tomatoes (probably the most reliable critic's consensus site around) out of around 189 critic reviews. It is entertaining and at least is more sophisticated than Twilight, though it is more that than the far superior Hunger Games, but it is messily directed and lacklustre. I felt the usually brilliant Kate Winslet gave a disappointingly lazy performance as the villain, I didn't feel the icy menace or the darkness that, say, Donald Sunderland as President Snow (The Hunger Games franchise) or Ralph Fiennes as Lord Voldemort/Tom Riddle (The Harry Potter franchise, needless to say) portrays. And as for the lead, Shailene Woodley is no Jennifer Lawrence (who is, quite obviously, the new Meryl Streep with her sheer, effortless talent and charisma), lacking the emotional depth and sexiness; she is pretty but has more in common with Kristen Stewart, however, I predict that this film franchise will continue and in terms of commercial success, become the new Twilight, but if it wants to be better than that, then Lionsgate or Summit Entertainment must start with getting a new director to direct Insurgent, the second instalment, which it already has in "Red" director Robert Schwintke. I'm neutral on this decision and I'm not sure what he'll bring to the Divergent franchise, but I hope it's better, I hope it's good and I hope Insurgent is realized perfectly in every way sense.

text: Divergent >>> Hunger Games. Since we feel like comparing them. There we go :) Divergent just had a much more enjoyable atmosphere. There was not ONE scene in the books/movies that bored me. I couldn't but the books down or look away from the screen where as Hunger Games there were so many parts(mostly everything besides the arena) where I was bored out of my mind. That and Katniss was annoying as hell(except Jennifer Lawrence <3). I also feel like the Divergent books went more in-depth with the characters and the events in the book. In Hunger Games there were characters who appeared then disappeared and were never heard of again(like all the surviving characters after the war???) and the events just happened so fast it's as if Suzanne Collins was in a rush to get it published. Don't get me wrong I did enjoy THG and CF but Divergent in my opinion is LIGHT YEARS better.

text: Divergent is mixed bag to me. There are pros and cons with this picture. First i have to say Shailene Woodley is great young actress and her portrayal of Tris was very good if not great, plot of the film was interesting enough to keep me invested for the most part, supporting cast was also decent although i don't see people connecting to them like in the Hunger Games, movie looks fine and action is filmed well. But, there are way too many issues with it to say it's good.There is nothing at stake here, movie is way too long(they could cut about 20 - 30 minutes easily), it doesn't make sense, there is no character development so it is very hard to care about people here, some scenes go way too long, romanse is cliched, there is no strong villain and movie felt contrived and preposterous in the end. 2.5 / 5
author: ogorjefan

text: Watched it... Basically another film made for the teens. The first hour was fairly alright, kept my interest going. The next hour was kind of insufferable... (SPOILERS!) The film took a slow climb to its 'climax', and it was another one of those films that centered around a character that was unique and had a different character/mindset compared to all the others. It just makes us question, why him/her, or why just this one person, who thinks so differently and was able to make a difference, alter the course of events?  And yes like someone else mentioned, why is it always a couple, the love, the bond... Clearly, it was digging into teenagers' mindset. This film could have been more if it was about someone who met like-minded peers in that society, and then when overcoming great difficulty, he/she rose out of her peers. That could have been more acceptable.

text: This movie was not good. Some scenes were nicely done but it seems they were there only to add some depth to the location, as most of the actual story takes place in awfully boring, under-detailed sets. The acting was sub-par and bland. The story borrows this and that from every other dystopian rebellion movie/book and feels mostly unoriginal.  I found there to be very little character attachment to the audience. I felt like I didn't care who survived or who died, mostly because everyone who died had almost no character development. It was also disappointing to see them throw in a very loose, empty relationship that was quite unimportant in the story, and it seems they only tried to jam it in there just to have one.

text: i watched this last night and i'm sure it hits the mark with its target market audience, that being the same for 'the hunger games' and to a lesser extent, 'twilight.' in that sense, it's a successful film... probably.  to anyone that knows how formulaic, hollywood-ized, and by-the-numbers this movie is, well, not so much. i think most would agree the performances were good overall, but might not agree with the balance of the actual story. i felt the 'plot' was sporatic and an afterthought, all too easily wrapped up in the end.   predictable and, imo, uneven to an adult, the young adult set is likely to dig it, even if it's similar to 'the hunger games'' hilariously cheesy 80's sci-fi premise. for me, it was simply the hollywood formula that got in the way. granted, i'm probably more familiar with plot points and such than some folk, but anyone that pays attention to movies should recognize what's going to happen given the typical clues like foreshadowing, call-backs, whatever.   i didn't buy the romance. this world seems to be run by kids, where anyone over 25 seems out of place, hiding secrets, is corrupt and are the ones who just doesn't get it. not that the secondary characters aren't expected to be one-dimensional plot generators, but they're nothing more, so you can't be disappointed, but.... the world itself is simplistic, under-developed, and cliche where each faction have their own colour clothes. really, the premise of this world might be insulting to some people's intelligence.   well, anyway, it's a silly premise designed to appeal to a different market, and since the plot points are so standard, not to mention the unbalanced feeling of the plot vs. character development (which triss is the only one that's not cliched all to hell), and i'd say anyone with more, ah, 'discriminate' tastes might want to skip this one. if you're a younger female without much story/movie experience, it might seem new and interesting. :)

text: this girl has some serious talent as an actress! blew my mind! i'd call this, more believable approach than the Hunger Games. this one actually makes sense for the most part. Hunger Games is just a shit storm of stupidity compared to the idea behind this one. sure, Hunger Games is more popular... but that doesn't mean its better. it made more money... again, doesn't make it better. the Character of Triss, is also MUCH more believable than the character of Katniss... it actually shows Triss training, pushing herself to become better, yet she only get a little better... Katniss, your made to believe shes the best archer around... meanwhile, she's self taught? because she hunts animals? no. that's just foolish. when hunting animals, your are patient, and the animal is usually still, until it is disturbed, or moves on. i don't mind Hunger Games, i simply saw alot of similarities between the 2, didn't mean to actually bag on the movie, was simple comparisons.  Shailene Woodley is an extraordinary actress! believable character play, raw emotion, excellent emotional and physically control. Jennifer Lawrence is well known, and acting is mediocre at best, with some raw, yet seemingly forced emotions.  not a fan of Jen, as she is self admittedly very dumb. both movies are amusing, but 1 is more believable than the other.  this is my opinion, don't have to agree with me, and don't have to like it.

text: There's a comment conversation down below saying how Tobias isn't Divergent. A lot of people claimed that he is because it says so in the first book and in the additional SEPERATE series about Tobias BEFORE and a few parts of AFTER Tris transfers to Dauntless, called FOUR. The person that claimed he isn't is right, Tobias is NOT Divergent. In the first two books and in the Four series, everyone thinks he is Divergent because he is aware during simulations. In Allegiant- the last book in the Divergent series- you find out what Divergent is and that Tobias is NOT Divergent, it's just that his body has somehow activated the simulation awareness trait that all Divergents have. Read the series people, and stop acting like you know the series so well if you've only watched the movie and are only basing your knowledge of the Divergent series or just one of the books based on the movie. Movie fans, answer these questions please:   Who's Uriah?   Where were Tobias and Tris during their first kiss?  What were ALL the events that occured IN Tris's aptitude test simulation?   Who is Edward?  What is a Pansycake?   What is the dessert that is famous in the Dauntless faction?  Answer with knowledge based on the MOVIE please, unless you have read at least ALL THREE BOOKS.

text: When I was a kid, my favourite toy was an airplane, by PlayMobil.  It did not fly, but you could pull it along the ground with a string, and pretend it was in the clouds. And the top opened, like kitchen door cabinets, and you could see the people, the passengers and employees. After a while, the captain was sitting in a seat while the stewardess was flying. That toy was very educational. It taught me that roles, are like boxes, and anybody can occupy a role. But the world is cruel - If you look like a stewardess, they will treat you like a stewardess. Well, how should a stewardess look? Why not this guy, or that other passenger, wearing a business suit? Could that not be a stewardess? Roles, occupations, are oft alike, and all involve carrying out instructions, and moving something from A to B. Cooking, chemistry, pulling levers, moving luggage, boxes really .. Force equals mass times acceleration .. See, gender neutral? Intelligence - this before that. I miss that toy, because it was food for thought. And so is that movie, A Little Chaos (Kate Winslet). Some like to diverge from the path others choose for them. It is evidence that they are awake, is it not?

text: Anyone who thinks that Divergent is like the Hunger Games is seriously an idiot. I mean first of all, sure both movies are dystopian movies but the themes are completely different. Divergent is based on a futuristic society where people are brought up in their factions which value one, distinct quality, and so they are brainwashed to only have that one,distinct quality. But there are certain people like us that are normal and have several different qualities and are thus called Divergents. There is no specific categorization in the Hunger Games. People are randomly put and brought into random districts. Also the Hunger Games is based on the games which people are forced to do that serve as a reminder from the Capitol that the people are under their control. In Divergent there is nothing like that except that Jeanine Mathews wants to eradicate the basic fundamental laws of human nature. She wants to make sure that people value faction before blood. Although in both movies, there is a rebellion, (in Mockingjay the people rebel to the Capitol, and in Divergent the people rebel indirectly to suppress killing Divergents), the reason for these rebellions is completely different because the problems in both the separate movies is different. You people who think that just because there is some government such as the Capitol and a rebellion in both the movies, you think that both movies are the same. That's not true because the message that each movie conveys is completely different. Divergent conveys a message about what could happen if our very own futuristic society were to turn into some scary utopia, and that if we had a certain categorization based entirely on people's personalities, the conclusion would be would this, disastrous and mind-blowing. The games in the Hunger Games are purely for entertainment and it is based on how Katniss sparks a rebellion in the people to change the way things are because it is wrong to watch people dying and enjoying it and calling it 'games'. Both movies reflect a certain problem in the society that has always been the perfect definition/example of a society at least in the perspective of  the leadership/Capitol, but the fault in the societies is completely different, and the truth is that neither society is perfect. And the way the two protagonists (Katniss and Tris) handle these problems is also different. Please do not say that these movies are the same or that Divergent is a ripoff of the Hunger Games because it is truly not. Sorry about that whole essay but I am sick of these hateful comments towards Divergent. Divergent has a completely different plot, story line, message, climax and ending to the Hunger Games. Each movie stands on its own and neither movie should be compared to each other because each of these movies has it's own identity.This is just to the people that are saying that these movies are alike, hopefully this will keep your mouths shut

text: before anything else i want to say that i haven't read the books, so my statement is fully based on the movie. if there's explanation about the topic in the books but not in the movie, i apologize for my ignorance.  so, the movie was great - one of my favorites if i have to be honest.   the thing i don't really understand about this whole "divergent", "different" thing is why are the divergents such a big deal? yeah, they are different, they fit in too many factions and all but why are they considered as such a threat? if there has to be something that threatens the government, wouldn't it be factionless people? I know that they are considered as "the garbage" of society exactly because they don't fit anywhere. but just think about it. these people don't fit in any faction you could possibly know. they can have many other qualities and strengths you're not aware of. plus, they can't be controlled by the government since they don't fit in their standards, could they? just like the divergents. and then we have fucking Janine worrying about a person who fits in ALL factions KNOWN by society.   anyways, this still stays a bomb ass movie.

How exactly to divide people by attitudes and behaviors helps avoid a war? And how exactly they CONTROL that? I mean, if you are "Candor" and you jump from a train, probably you are a risk for the society? Or if you are "Erudite" you can't be honest or selfless or you can be suspicious (or "divergent")? And if you are Abnegation you should always dress like a poor or a fool with the same color?.   That form of stereotyping and self-stereotyping people like a f"#"king object can be normal in the "society" (gangs) of the teenagers, but it's really idiotic even as a metaphor, despite all the action scenes.

text: Imagine two groups, X and Y.  If a member of X is able to breakaway  and join group Y, we would say that  members of X are free.  But if members  of group Y are not free to leave, we would  call that a prison.  Beware of stickiness  and lock-in.  Christianity - many different  factions, but members of one group, or  denomination, seem free to breakaway  and join another.  "I was Amity but am now  Dauntless", that sort of thing.  But one can  get into serious trouble having one foot in  the Catholic camp, and the other in the  Protestant Camp.  I hate the team sport  mentality, and prefer to be as a free agent,  decidedly undecided.
